Six months into any NestJS project you feel the drag. You add a field for one feature and a test breaks in another you’ve never touched. A new teammate asks “where does the order logic live?” and the honest answer is “…a bit everywhere.”
Nobody wrote bad code. You just organized it by the wrong thing. This is a short field guide to the parts of Domain-Driven Design that actually pay of call it selective DDD.
I’ll teach them on a plain e-commerce backend (orders, catalog, payments, shipping) because you already know how that domain behaves, and every snippet includes the part most articles skip: how it actually works.

Rule 1 — Don’t make one model serve the whole app
Every messy backend has a God class. It’s called Order, it has thirty nullable columns, and everything imports it. One day a change the warehouse needed breaks checkout.
Look closely and that one Order is really three different things wearing one name:

• Checkout wants a cart: prices, discounts, a payment intent.

• Fulfillment wants a pick-list of SKUs and an address — and nothing about discounts.

• Billing wants an amount and an invoice number.
Force them into one class and everyone is coupled to everyone else’s concerns. The fix: give each area its own model, and let them cooperate by passing a small message, not by sharing a class.
orders ──"order #123 placed, here are its SKUs"──► fulfillmentEach area — orders, catalog, fulfillment, billing — is a bounded context: a walled-off slice with its own model, where a word like “order” means exactly one thing. This isn’t a microservices rule — in a monolith a context is a top-level group of modules that owns its own tables; in microservices it’s a separate service. Either way: no shared model across the wall.
The test: a change inside one context shouldn’t force edits in another. If it constantly does, your walls are in the wrong place.

Rule 2 — A module is a domain, not a layer
Your PM asks for gift-wrapping on orders. Watch what it costs in a project organized by technical role:
src/
├── controllers/ # order, auth, product, shipment, payment...
├── services/ # order, auth, product, shipment, payment...
├── entities/
└── enums/ # every enum in the whole appYou open controllers/, scroll past auth and shipping to find the order one. Then services/, same scroll. Then entities/, enums/. Five folders, five scrolls, and the feature is smeared across all of them.
This layout is built for the question “show me all controllers” — which nobody asks. The real question is “show me everything about orders.” So group by domain first:
modules/orders/
├── controllers/
├── dto/
├── entities/
│ ├── order.entity.ts
│ └── order-status.enum.ts # the enum sits next to what it uses
├── repositories/
└── orders.module.tsNow gift-wrapping is one folder. Note there’s no global enums/ — an enum describes one thing, so it lives beside that thing. One guardrail: common/ is for things with no domain (pagination, base repository). The moment common/ knows what an order is, it has leaked into a module.

Rule 3 — Modules depend on interfaces, not each other’s services
Two features land the same week. The product page needs “in 3 open orders.” The receipt needs product names. So catalog injects OrderService and orders injects ProductService. Nest stops you cold:
Nest cannot create the CatalogModule instance.
- A circular dependency between modules. Use forwardRef() to avoid it.forwardRef() makes the error go away and welds the two modules together forever. The real fix: depend on a small interface you own, not on another module's service.
catalog needs to refuse deleting a product that's still in an open order — but only orders knows that. So catalog declares the question and lets someone else answer it:
export interface ProductUsageGuard {
isProductInUse(productId: string): Promise<boolean>;
}orders implements it and registers itself; catalog just asks, without importing anyone:
for (const guard of this.guards) {
if (await guard.isProductInUse(id)) throw new ProductInUseError(id);
}Before: catalog ⇄ orders circular — Nest won't boot
After: catalog ◄──implements── orders one way — catalog owns the interfaceThe arrow points one way — no cycle, no forwardRef(). Bonus: when someone later adds "can't delete a product in an active subscription," the subscriptions module registers its own guard and catalog doesn't change a line.

Rule 4 — Thin controllers, rich entities
“You can’t cancel an order that already shipped.” Where does that rule live? In most codebases, wherever someone first needed it — inside a service. Then the admin panel needs to cancel too, and the nightly job, and a webhook. Each grows its own copy of the check. Someone writes the fourth and forgets it, and now you’re refunding orders that already left the warehouse.
An entity that’s just public fields, mutated from outside, is an anemic model, and this is how it fails: the rules leak into — and get duplicated across — every service.
Put the rule on the object that owns the data:
@Entity()
export class Order {
status: OrderStatus = OrderStatus.DRAFT;cancel(): void {
if (this.status === OrderStatus.SHIPPED) {
throw new Error('Cannot cancel an order that already shipped');
}
this.status = OrderStatus.CANCELLED;
}Now there’s one definition of “cancel,” and no caller can skip the check — there’s nowhere else to put it. It’s also testable in three lines, no database. The service just orchestrates (order.cancel(), then refund, then save) and the controller is a one-liner:
@Post(':id/cancel')
cancel(@Param('id') id: string) {
return this.orders.cancel(id);
}The split, at a glance:
HTTP ─► Controller ─► Service ─► Order (the rules)
└─────► Repository ─► DB (the queries)Entities own the rules, repositories own the queries, services own the sequence, controllers own the HTTP.

Rule 5 — Make bad states impossible to build
Rule 4 put rules on entities. Two smaller patterns finish the job — and both kill a specific bug.
Value objects — for a primitive that has rules. An order total is a number, so nothing stops a coupon from driving it negative, or a EUR refund from being added to a USD order. The rules of "money" live nowhere. Give money a type that enforces them:
export class Money {
private constructor(readonly cents: number, readonly currency: string) {} static of(cents: number, currency: string): Money {
if (cents < 0) throw new Error('Money cannot be negative');
return new Money(cents, currency);
}
add(o: Money): Money {
if (o.currency !== this.currency) throw new Error('Currency mismatch');
return Money.of(this.cents + o.cents, this.currency);
}
}
Now a negative or mixed-currency total is impossible to construct. That’s a value object: a small immutable type defined by its value, not an id. Reach for one when a primitive has rules you keep re-checking (money, email, CIDR); skip it for a bare id.
Aggregates — for a rule that spans objects. An order’s total must equal the sum of its lines. Give OrderLine its own repository and someone will save a line without updating the order — total silently wrong. So don't. Make Order the aggregate root: the only object you load and save, the one door in. No OrderLineRepository; you change lines through the order:
addLine(sku: string, price: Money, qty: number): void {
if (this.status !== OrderStatus.DRAFT) throw new Error('Order already placed');
this.lines.push(new OrderLine(sku, price, qty));
this.total = this.sumOfLines();
}One door means the invariant can’t be broken. Keep aggregates small (only what must change in the same transaction) and reference other aggregates by id, not by object.

Rule 6 — Announce events, don’t summon services
Checkout works, so place() grows: it saves the order, then calls shipping, then billing, then email. Now orders imports half the app and knows every downstream step. Add loyalty points next quarter and you're editing checkout again — for something that has nothing to do with checkout.
Flip it. orders does its job and announces a fact — it doesn't know who's listening:
this.events.emit(new OrderPlaced(order.id, order.customerId, items));Each context reacts on its own:
@OnEvent(OrderPlaced.name)
handle(e: OrderPlaced) { return this.shipping.createShipment(e); }Adding loyalty points is now a new listener in the loyalty module — orders never changes. Across separate services it's the same idea over a message broker (RabbitMQ, in my case), with one addition: a transactional outbox — you write the event into an outbox table in the same transaction as the order, and a worker publishes it afterwards. Skip that and a crash between "order saved" and "event published" loses the event silently. In production it's the difference between reliable and haunted.
One caveat: events hide the flow, so a reader can’t see the whole sequence in one place. Use them for cross-context reactions, not for steps inside a single job.

The payoff
Follow all six and here’s what you actually get:

• Change one area without breaking three. Each context owns its model, so a fix in fulfillment can’t ripple into checkout.

• Find any feature in one place. A task lives in a single folder — no five-folder scavenger hunt to ship gift-wrapping.

• Swap and extend without rewrites. Depending on interfaces lets you replace Stripe with PayPal, add a rule, or split out a service — and never hit a boot-time cycle.

• A rule that can’t be skipped or duplicated. “Can’t cancel a shipped order” has exactly one home, and it’s unit-testable in three lines with no database.

• Whole bug classes stop compiling. A negative total, a mixed-currency sum, an order that disagrees with its own line items — impossible to even construct.

• New behavior is additive. Next quarter’s feature is a new event listener; the code that already works is never reopened.
The whole point: a newcomer navigates by reading folder names, and the boundaries hold because the compiler and the DI container won’t let them break — not because everyone remembered to be careful.
